{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/dermatitis-contact/background-information/common-allergens-irritants/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"32cc4e93-9611-54f1-aea5-e6d6b6953f22","slug":"common-allergens-irritants","fullItemName":"Common allergens and irritants","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 15a9d59a-9911-45b4-a3f1-69c34c972eaa --><h2>What are the common allergens and irritants?</h2><!-- end field 15a9d59a-9911-45b4-a3f1-69c34c972eaa -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b2c61dfb-181a-41a5-9e70-772400bdc900 --><!-- begin field 9c2834b2-d159-45ac-89e2-5f27b684ddec --><ul><li><strong>Common allergens include:</strong><ul><li>Personal care products such as cosmetics, skin care products, nail varnish, fragrances, sun screen and hair dye.</li><li>Metals such as nickel and cobalt (often found in jewellery) and chromate (in cement) – nickel is the most common allergen.</li><li>Topical medications including anti-infective agents and topical corticosteroids.</li><li>Rubber additives (often found in footware).</li><li>Plants – compositae group (chrysanthemum and sunflowers), daffodils, tulips, and primula are the most common.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Common irritants include:</strong><ul><li>Water, in particular repeated or prolonged contact, such as with wet working conditions. </li><li>Sweating under occlusion.</li><li>Detergents, soaps and cleaning agents.</li><li>Solvents and abrasives.</li><li>Machine and cutting oils.</li><li>Acids and alkalis (including cement).</li><li>Reducing agents and oxidizing agents (including sodium hypochlorite).</li><li>Powders, dust and soil (such as exotic woods and cement).</li><li>Certain plants such as ranunculus, spurge, boracinaceae and mustards.</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>The risk of contact dermatitis may be increased in certain occupations:</strong></p><ul><li>Data from the UK national occupational health surveillance scheme (EPIDERM) based on annual case reports of skin disease by dermatologists found that between 2007–2016 [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">HSE, 2017</a>]:<ul><li>The highest rates of occupational dermatitis were reported in florists, hairdressers and barbers, beauticians, cooks, and metal working machine operatives.</li><li>Healthcare workers (such as nurses and dental practitioners) also had a high incidence of occupational dermatitis (over 25 new cases per 100,000 per year).</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Admani, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Tan, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Fonacier, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">HSE, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Mostosi, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Rashid, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">White, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Wilkinson, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">BAD, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dermatitis-contact/references/\">Fonacier, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 9c2834b2-d159-45ac-89e2-5f27b684ddec --><!-- end item b2c61dfb-181a-41a5-9e70-772400bdc900 -->","topic":{"id":"a372c7ca-356b-58f9-8c90-6f20d1b6df4b","topicId":"ed82aa3c-29ae-494e-a0d6-a1e528deec8e","topicN